Categorical variable examples: species, island, sex

Numeric variable examples: bill length/depth, flipper length, body mass


  1. Let’s make a bar graph of the penguin species. Change the border around the bars to be white.
ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = species),
           color = "white")


  1. See what happens when you map the variable sex to the fill argument. (Note: Should fill go inside or outside of aes()? How do you know?)
ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = species,
               fill = sex),
           color = "white")

What happens when we map a variable to fill in a bar graph?: The bar is split into different colors depending on which category each observation falls into. For this example, the species bar (x) is split into color based on sex (fill).


  1. Try adding the argument position = "fill" to your geom_bar() function. What does this do? Why might we want to view the graph this way?
ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = species,
               fill = sex),
           color = "white",
           position = "fill")

What does position = "fill" do?: It converts the y-axis from measuring counts to measuring proportions. Without this argument, we could see how many penguins are from each species broken down by sex. With this argument, we can see the proportion of each species that belongs to a certain sex.

What is the benefit of viewing the graph like this?: This makes it much easier to compare proportions across groups. I can easily see that there are similar proportions of male/female penguins among the three species.


  1. Next, make a side-by-side boxplot of bill_length_mm by species where the lines around each boxplot are lightblue.
ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm,
                   y = species),
               color = "lightblue")
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_boxplot()`).


  1. Add an argument that maps sex to fill. What does this do?
ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm,
                   y = species,
                   fill = sex),
               color = "lightblue")
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_boxplot()`).

What does mapping a new variable to fill do?: It creates separate boxplots for each sex that each have a different color. This is done within the grouping that we already started with (species).


  1. There’s no easy way to remove the NA boxes without removing them from the data. Try replacing penguins in your ggplot() function with filter(penguins, !is.na(sex)) and re-run your code. What is !is.na(sex) doing?
# Note: You need to load dplyr for the filter() funciton to work. I added this
#   at the top of my code with my other packages.

ggplot(filter(penguins, !is.na(sex))) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm,
                   y = species,
                   fill = sex),
               color = "lightblue")

What is !is.na(sex) doing?: The is.na() function is looking for all of the missing values within the sex variable. By adding an ! before the function, I’m now looking for values that are not missing.


  1. One easy way to improve or customize the look of our graphs is to add a theme. We can do this by adding another function to our graphing object we are creating (like we added geom_boxplot() to ggplot()). Try adding theme_xx() where xx is one of the following: bw, classic, dark, minimal, void. You may want to try multiple options until you find one you like best. You can also see examples here if you scroll down.
library(dplyr)
ggplot(filter(penguins, !is.na(sex))) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm,
                   y = species,
                   fill = sex),
               color = "lightblue") +
  theme_classic()


  1. We’ve seen what happens when we map a variable to fill/color for bar graphs and box plots. Let’s see how that works with histograms. Create a histogram of body_mass_g and map species to fill.
ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = body_mass_g, fill = species))
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_bin()`).


  1. In our histogram, the three species are stacked on top of one another, which makes it hard to see how many of each there are. One option is to create separate histograms for each species. We can do this using the facet_wrap() function. To do this, add a layer to your graph that says facet_wrap(vars(species)).
ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = body_mass_g, fill = species)) +
  facet_wrap(vars(species)) +
  theme_bw()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_bin()`).


  1. If we want to control how many rows or columns the graphs are put into, we can use the nrow = __ or ncol = __ arguments. Try using one of those arguments to stack the three histograms on top of one another. What’s an advantage to viewing the graphs this way?
ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = body_mass_g, fill = species)) +
  facet_wrap(vars(species), ncol = 1) +
  theme_bw()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_bin()`).

Advantage to stacking the graphs: In this graph, my histograms all use the same x-axis values which allows me to more easily compare how the body masses differ across species.


  1. We can use a different function called facet_grid() to create a grid of graphs corresponding to our different variables. Take our histogram from question 9 and add facet_grid(rows = vars(sex), cols = vars(species)) to it. (Note: If you want to remove NAs, go back to how we previously accomplished that).
ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = body_mass_g, fill = species)) +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(sex),
             cols = vars(species)) +
  theme_bw()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_bin()`).
